col_missing <- sapply(vehicles, function(col) sum(is.na(col)))
median_odometer <- median(vehicles$odometer, na.rm = TRUE)
vehicles$odometer[is.na(vehicles$odometer)] <- median_odometer

# Drop rows with missing lat or long values
vehicles <- vehicles[!is.na(vehicles$lat) & !is.na(vehicles$long),]


vehicles <- vehicles[!is.na(vehicles$posting_date),]
# Example: Drop the county column
vehicles$county <- NULL
# For a continuous variable like 'odometer'
vehicles$odometer[is.na(vehicles$odometer)] <- mean(vehicles$odometer, na.rm = TRUE)

# For a categorical variable like 'fuel'
mode_fuel <- as.character(names(sort(table(vehicles$fuel), decreasing=TRUE)[1]))
vehicles$fuel[is.na(vehicles$fuel)] <- mode_fuel
# Check for missing values in each column
sapply(vehicles, function(col) sum(is.na(col)))

library(data.table)

# Convert to numeric
vehicles[, price := as.numeric(price)]
vehicles[, year := as.numeric(year)]

# Ensure no errors occurred during conversion
vehicles[!is.finite(price), price := NA]
vehicles[!is.finite(year), year := NA]
vehicles[drive == "", drive := NA]
vehicles[size == "", size := NA]
# Treat vehicles with a price of 0 as missing values
vehicles[price == 0, price := NA]

# Treat extremely high prices (e.g., above 1 million) as missing values
vehicles[price > 1e6, price := NA]
summary(vehicles$price)

#Minimum: The minimum price is now 1. While this is still very low for a vehicle, it is more plausible than a price of zero. #1st Quartile: The first quartile (25th percentile) price is 7,000, suggesting that 25% of the vehicles are priced at 7,000 or less. #Median: The median price (50th percentile) is 15,000, meaning half of the vehicles are priced below this and half are priced above. #Mean: The average price of the vehicles is 18,912. #3rd Quartile: The third quartile (75th percentile) price is 27,590, meaning 75% of vehicles are priced below this value. #Maximum: The maximum price is 1,000,000, which, although high, is plausible for certain luxury or collectors vehicles. #NAs: There are 29,888 vehicles with missing price values (either originally missing or set to NA during our cleaning).

# Convert all character columns to lowercase
char_cols <- names(vehicles)[sapply(vehicles, is.character)]
vehicles[, (char_cols) := lapply(.SD, tolower), .SDcols = char_cols]

Data Dictionary

#This section provides a descriptive breakdown of the variables in the dataset:

Variable Description Type
id Unique identifier for vehicle Numeric
region Regional listing of vehicle Character
price Price of the vehicle Numeric
year Year of manufacture Numeric
manufacturer Manufacturer of the vehicle Character
model Model name of the vehicle Character
condition Condition of the vehicle (e.g., good, fair) Character
cylinders Number of cylinders in the engine Character
fuel Fuel type (e.g., gas, diesel) Character
odometer Miles driven Numeric
title_status Title status (e.g., clean, salvage) Character
transmission Type of transmission (e.g., automatic, manual) Character
drive Drive type (e.g., 4wd, fwd) Character
size Size of the vehicle (e.g., full-size, compact) Character
type Type of vehicle (e.g., sedan, truck) Character
paint_color Color of the vehicle Character
state US State of the listing Character
lat Latitude of the listing Numeric
long Longitude of the listing Numeric
posting_date Date of the posting Date

Data Cleaning & Preprocessing

Upon importing the dataset, the following preprocessing steps were taken:

  1. Duplicates: Duplicates were identified and removed to ensure that each listing in the dataset is unique.
  2. Age of Car: We transformed the year column to reflect the age of the vehicle. This was done by subtracting the year of manufacture from the current year. The original year column was then dropped as it became redundant.
  3. Dropping Columns: Certain columns like url, image_url, description, VIN, and region_url were removed. This decision was based on the assumption that these columns would not provide significant insight into our analysis.

# Load ggplot2
library(ggplot2)

# Select categorical variables
categorical_vars <- c("region", "manufacturer", "model", "condition", "cylinders", 
                      "fuel", "title_status", "transmission", "drive", "size", 
                      "type", "paint_color", "state")

# Loop through each variable and create a boxplot
for (cat_var in categorical_vars) {
  plot <- ggplot(vehicles, aes_string(x = cat_var, y = "price")) + 
          geom_boxplot() + 
          labs(title = paste("Boxplot of Price by", cat_var)) + 
          theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
  print(plot)
}

Summary: The regression model attempts to predict the price of a vehicle based on its manufacturer, age of the car, odometer reading, and transmission type.

Residuals: These values tell you about the distribution of the residuals (predicted - observed values). A more uniform distribution of residuals around zero would be ideal. In this case, there are some large positive and negative residuals, suggesting that there might be some outliers or extreme values affecting the model.

Coefficients: Intercept: The estimated price (in dollars) when all predictors are zero (or at their reference levels). The intercept is $30,140. manufacturer: Each coefficient here indicates the difference in the estimated price of a vehicle from the reference category (which is not listed in the output). For instance, vehicles by manufacturer acura are, on average, $5,168 less expensive than the reference category when all other variables are held constant. age_of_car: With every year increase in the age of a car, its price decreases by $472. This is consistent with the general understanding that older cars tend to be cheaper. odometer: For every additional mile on the odometer, the price decreases by $0.00739. This implies that cars with higher mileage are priced lower. transmission: Compared to the reference transmission category, automatic transmission cars are on average $2,564 cheaper, manual transmission cars are $1,061 more expensive, and other types of transmissions are $5,273 more expensive. Significance Codes: The asterisks next to the coefficients represent the significance levels:

: Highly significant (p < 0.001) : Significant at 0.01 level (0.001 < p < 0.01) : Significant at 0.05 level (0.01 < p < 0.05) For instance, the manufacturerland rover coefficient is not statistically significant since it doesnt have any asterisks next to its value.

Model Fit: Residual Standard Error: This is the average amount that the response will deviate from the true regression line. In this case, its $14,240. Multiple R-squared: This value (0.2335) tells us that approximately 23.35% of the variability in the price is explained by the model. Its a measure of how well the model fits the data. In general, a higher R-squared indicates a better fit. Adjusted R-squared: It adjusts the R-squared for the number of predictors in the model. In this case, its almost identical to R-squared, which means adding predictors hasnt overly complicated the model. F-statistic & p-value: The F-statistic tests the hypothesis that the model with no predictors fits the data as well as your model. A low p-value (< 2.2e-16) indicates that your model fits the data better than the intercept-only model. Notes: The age_of_car and odometer variables are highly significant, suggesting they are important predictors of price. Most manufacturers are significant predictors of price as well, with some (like ferrari) having a much larger positive effect than others. The dataset has some missing values since 30,999 observations were deleted due to missingness. Considerations: The R-squared suggests that while the model captures some of the variability, a large portion (around 76.65%) remains unexplained. Additional variables or more advanced modeling techniques might help improve this. The large residuals in the summary suggest that there are potentially some outliers or influential points that might be unduly affecting the models fit. It could be useful to investigate these further. Its essential to validate this model on a separate test set to assess its predictive performance.
